**Abstract:**
Philosophical response or working notes engaging with John Caputo's Derridean position on language, textuality, and presence. Argues against Caputo/Derrida's claim that language cannot deliver reality in presence, proposing instead Xavier's concept of "dramatic presence" (effective, exposed presence) versus "phenomenal presence." References Xavier's own paper "On McIntyre, Rationality and Dramatic Space" and suggests narrative discourse as the appropriate form for dramatic presence. Concludes that Derridean linguistic deconstructionism fails to open space for "the faith of faith."

**AI Recommendation:** Keep in undated/notes - philosophical working notes

